Preparation_Time_min¶

In [134]:
def classify_preparation_time_min(x):
    classification = {
        0<=x<=9: 'Quick preparation',
        10<=x<=19: 'Medium preparation',
        20<=x: 'Slow preparation',
    }
    return classification[True]

df.loc[:,'Preparation_Time_min_Classification'] = df.loc[:,'Preparation_Time_min'].apply(lambda x: classify_preparation_time_min(x))
df

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns

def plot_bars(df, column):
    count = df[column].value_counts()
    plt.bar(df[column].unique(), count)
    plt.title(column)
    plt.show()

def plot_lines(df, column_x, column_y):
    x = list(df[column_x])
    y = list(df[column_y])
    xy = []
    for i in range(len(df)):
        xy.append((x[i], y[i]))
    xy_sorted = sorted(xy, key = lambda item: item[0])
    
    x_sorted = []
    y_sorted = []
    for i,j in xy_sorted:
        x_sorted.append(i)
        y_sorted.append(j)
    plt.plot(x_sorted, y_sorted)
    plt.xlabel(column_x)
    plt.ylabel(column_y)
    plt.show()
plot_lines(df, 'Preparation_Time_min', 'Delivery_Time_min')
plot_lines(df, 'Courier_Experience_yrs', 'Delivery_Time_min')

Follows the shown plots, it is not correlation between the numeric data and the target data

### y = Delivery_Time_min

# colors = Vehicle_Type
def plot_scatterplot(df, column, column_x, column_y):
    uniques = df[column].unique()
    for i in uniques:
        plt.plot(df[df[column] == i][column_x], df[df[column] == i][column_y], '.')
        plt.xlabel(column_x)
        plt.ylabel(column_y)
        plt.legend(uniques)
        plt.title(column)
    plt.show()

early_stopping = EarlyStopping(

    patience=20, # how many epochs to wait before stopping

import tensorflow as tf
from tensorflow.keras.models import Sequential
from tensorflow.keras.layers import Dense
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler
import numpy as np
import pandas as pd

# Normalizar las características
scaler = StandardScaler()
X_train = scaler.fit_transform(X_train)
X_test = scaler.transform(X_test)

# Crear el modelo
model = Sequential([
    Dense(64, activation='relu', input_shape=(X_train.shape[1],)),  # Primera capa oculta
    Dense(128, activation='relu'),  # Segunda capa oculta
    Dense(64, activation='relu'),  # Tercera capa oculta
    Dense(1)  # Capa de salida para regresión
])

# Compilar el modelo
model.compile(optimizer='adam', loss='mse', metrics=['mae'])

# Entrenar el modelo
history = model.fit(X_train, y_train, epochs=50, batch_size=32, validation_split=0.2)

# Evaluar el modelo
loss, mae = model.evaluate(X_test, y_test)
print(f"Mean Absolute Error en conjunto de prueba: {mae:.2f} minutos")

# Hacer predicciones
predicciones = model.predict(X_test[:5])
print("Predicciones para las primeras 5 muestras:", predicciones.flatten())
print("Valores reales:", y_test[:5])
